cs.PL, cs.DC, cs.SE, cs.LO, cs.SY. 

This paper is likely to belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) category as it introduces a new type system for a distributed object-oriented language. It also involves syntax, operational semantics, and a type checking algorithm. 

It could also belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) category as it deals with session types for distributed programming. 

The Software Engineering (cs.SE) category is also a possibility as the paper discusses modularization of session type implementations and encapsulation of local state. 

The Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) category is a possibility as the paper discusses a form of typestate supporting non-uniform objects, which involves reasoning about the dynamic behavior of objects. 

Finally, the Systems and Control (cs.SY) category is a possibility as the paper deals with integrating session types with object types, which could be seen as a form of system integration.
